b"But back to my original point -- and this is praise, not criticism -- but #Severance is not for EVERYONE. I know people who went out of their skin watching BEING JOHN MALKOVICH, COHERENCE and PLAYTIME. This show works like that. It's amazing."

b"DP Jessica Lee Gang\xc3\xa9 is brick-by-Kubrick perfect, but gawtDAMN the art & production design by Nick Francone, Jeremy Hindle & Angelica Borrero! They MUST have worked with costume designer Sarah Edwards -- ESPECIALLY for that first shot. You'll see."

b"...and then you've got @TramellTillman as the most calm, reassuring, I'm-so-disappointed-in-you office manager in the history of office managing. All he wants to do is help, and he's the scariest thing in the show."

b'But then you\'ve got @zachcherrygmail and @TramellTillman as these out-of-left-field personalities that make every scene even MORE tense. Zach does this nerve-scraping riff on "the annoying coworker" trope (no one can make the phrase "waffle party" sound more evil)...'
b'The cast are their usual brilliant selves. Adam Scott & Britt Lower & Yul Vasquez & Walken & Turturro & Arquette. Of COURSE. Wow.'

b'You\'re thrown by how they lay out the whole show in the FIRST episode -- you were expecting this big "journey into a mystery" -- until you realize (as do the characters) that this shit isn\'t simple AT ALL.'

b'Dan Erickson has done what writers like Urusla K. Le Guin, Kurt Vonnegut and James Tiptree Jr (Alice Bradley Sheldon) were able to achieve -- imagine a waaaaay-to-near future where ONE SIMPLE IDEA has exploded the world we know.'
b"His style has become so...un-frantic and UNNERVING on this show. You actually dread the CALM moments, because that's when you think of all the implications of what is (or what COULD be) going on."

b'I read that @robertpatrickT2 studied how praying mantises move and react. Sam way DeNiro studied crabs to create Travis Bickle. An incredible acting performance because he WILLED THE ACTING OUT OF IT.'

b"Every other scene he has this Zen passivity that is so unnerving. When he's rolling along the pavement after being face-shot and his face is almost...blissful? Brilliant. And VERY hard to pull off, day to day making a movie."

b'The emotions he shows are: 1) slightly annoyed the first time he fights the T-800 at the mall; 2) the taunting finger-wag (it\'s a "learning computer", remember) and 3) the shock when he takes the grenade to the belly.'

b"He's a genuinely expressive, emotional actor so the preparation he must have done every morning to be that CREEPILY EMOTIONLESS (he doesn't have a single human reaction until that final, disturbing finger-wag) was superhuman."

b"Re-watching TERMINATOR 2 after watching @robertpatrickT2's subsequent work (FIRE IN THE SKY, COP LAND, THE SOPRANOS and now PEACEMAKER) you realize what a brilliant performance the T-1000 was for him to pull off."
